Github:
is a "social coding" site. It allows you to upload code repositories for storage in the Git version control system. You can then collaborate on code projects, and the system is open-source by default, 
meaning that anyone in the world can find your GitHub code, use it, learn from it, and improve on it.

Github-Pages:

1. What is GitHub Pages?
GitHub Pages is a free static website hosting service provided by GitHub that allows developers to publish websites directly from a GitHub repository.

It is mainly used to host:
Static websites
Project documentation
Personal portfolios
Blogs
Demo pages for web applications

The website is automatically built and deployed from files stored in the repository.

Example URL format:

https://username.github.io/repository-name

If the repository is named:
username.github.io

Then the website becomes:
https://username.github.io

2. Key Features:

1. Free Static Hosting -   Allows developers to host websites without managing servers.

2. Automatic Deployment -  Whenever code is pushed to the repository, GitHub automatically updates the website.

3. Custom Domain Support - You can connect a custom domain like:
          www.myportfolio.com

4. Integration with Git -  Website content is version controlled and managed through Git.

5. Static Site Generators -  Supports generators like Jekyll to automatically convert Markdown into HTML pages.

3. Types of GitHub Pages Sites
1. User/Organization Site

Repository name:

username.github.io -  Website URL:https://username.github.io

Used mainly for:
  personal websites
  portfolios
  blogs

2. Project Site

Repository name can be anything: my-project  -   Website URL:https://username.github.io/my-project


Used mainly for:
project demos
project documentation

4. Basic Workflow
Step 1: Create a Repository

Create a repository on GitHub.

Example:

my-website

Step 2: Add Website Files

Example structure:

my-website
│
├── index.html
├── style.css
└── script.js


index.html acts as the homepage.

Step 3: Enable GitHub Pages

Go to Repository Settings

Select Pages

Under Source, choose:

Branch: main

Folder: /root

Click Save

Step 4: Access the Website

GitHub provides a public URL:

https://username.github.io/my-website

5. Folder Sources for GitHub Pages

GitHub Pages can build from:

Root Folder
/


Example:

index.html
style.css

Docs Folder
/docs


Example:

docs/
 ├── index.html
 └── guide.html

6. Advantages

Free hosting

Easy deployment

